3. Class Outliers

outliers_num <- boxplot.stats(pub_unique_id$NUMBER_PUBLICATIONS)$out

head(sort(outliers_num))
## [1] 14 14 14 14 14 14
tail(sort(outliers_num))
## [1] 1415 1417 1477 1567 1691 2211
sub_pub_unique_id <- subset(pub_unique_id$NUMBER_PUBLICATIONS, 
                            pub_unique_id$NUMBER_PUBLICATIONS < min(outliers_num) )
  • As we saw in the lecture Outliers should be detected, but not necessarily removed. Their inclusion in the analysis is a statistical decision. One potential issues after the first analysis was the outliers because as we said, we can not considered as accurate data a scientist who has published more than hundreds or thousands publications. The R language comes with function boxplot.stats, which, amongst other things, list the outliers. In this method, an observation is an outlier when it is larger than the so-called ``whiskers of the set of observations. The upper whisker is computed by adding 1.5 times the interquartile range to the third quartile and rounding to the nearest lower observation. The lower whisker is computed likewise.
